The exchange rate for a foreign ATM can be different than the one you see on Google or your bank's website because the ATM provider needs to make a profit from the exchange. They will typically offer an exchange rate that is less favourable than the market rate, and the difference is their profit. 
This is why it's often a good idea to avoid using foreign ATMs and to use a credit card that doesn't charge foreign transaction fees instead, or to withdraw cash from a local bank account if you have one.

For your issue: **Pending transfer** is a status of your bank transaction which means that the transaction has been submitted to the bank for processing. When your payment is pending, status of your transaction is being updated on your bank's platform and typically after 1-3 business days the transfer status should change to **Processed** if everything is correct with the transfer details, your account is active and all holds and blocks have been lifted.

If the transfer status remains pending and transfer cannot be completed, then there may be an issue with the transfer details - you may need to verify account details once again. To resolve the issue, contact the bank's support team for assistance.

Businesses in the financial sector, including currency exchange providers, often offer incentives to customers who frequently use their services. These incentives can come in the form of discounts, loyalty programs, or reward schemes.

Discounts for frequently exchanging currencies may be offered to customers who meet certain criteria, such as making a minimum number of transactions within a set period or transacting a minimum amount of money. These discounts can take the form of reduced exchange rates, waived fees, or points rewards.

Loyalty programs and reward schemes may offer perks such as VIP status, priority service, or enhanced exchange rates. To participate in these programs, customers typically need to make a minimum number of transactions or maintain a minimum balance.

It's important to note that the availability and terms of these incentives can vary widely between providers, so it's a good idea to shop around and compare offerings before choosing a currency exchange service.

If your card gets stuck in an ATM, there are a few steps you can take to try and retrieve it:

1. Try to retrieve the card: If the ATM has a "Cancel" or "Return" button, see if you can use it to retrieve your card.
2. Contact the ATM's owner: If the ATM is owned by a bank or other financial institution, contact them to see if they can help you retrieve your card. They may be able to unlock the ATM or dispatch someone to help you.
3. Contact your bank: Your bank may be able to help you cancel the card and issue a replacement. They may also be able to work with the ATM's owner to retrieve your card.
4. Report the incident: If your card has been stuck in the ATM for several days, report it to the police. They can help you file a report and keep an eye out for fraudulent activity on your account.

If the ATM is not owned by a bank or financial institution, it's possible that there is no one to contact for help. In this case, you may need to resort to more drastic measures. Do not attempt to force the ATM open or damage it in any way, as this could lead to criminal charges. Instead, try to flag down a passing police officer or call a locksmith.

If you notice a strange withdrawal on your bank statement, there a few steps you should take:

1. Review the transaction: Check the date, time, and amount of the transaction to make sure it's not a mistake or a purchase that you forgot about. Look for any unusual or suspicious activity, such as a different location or merchant name than what you're used to.

2. Contact the bank: If you believe that the transaction is unauthorized, contact your bank as soon as possible. They can investigate the transaction and determine if it needs to be disputed.

3. File a dispute: If the bank determines that the transaction is fraudulent, they will help you file a dispute. The process will vary depending on your bank's policies, but typically, they will ask you to complete a form with details of the transaction and any supporting documentation.

4. Monitor your account: After filing a dispute, continue to monitor your account for any other suspicious activity. If you notice anything unusual, contact the bank immediately.

5. Add a fraud alert: Consider adding a fraud alert to your credit report to protect your assets and mitigate the risk of further fraud. The alert will notify creditors that your identity has been compromised and they should take extra precautions when verifying your identity.
